===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|wepen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|wēpan||to weep, complain, bewail, mourn over, deplore}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*wōpijaną||to weep}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*wāb-||to call, cry, complain}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|wepe|lang=sco}}, {{term|weip||to weep|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|stq|-}} {{term|wapia||to cry, complain|lang=stq}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|æpa||to yell, shout|lang=is}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|weeps|weeping|'''[[wept]]''' or '''[[weeped]]'''}}

# To [[cry]]; [[shed tears]].
#* Longfellow
#*: They '''wept''' together in silence.
# To lament; to complain.
#* Bible, Numbers xi. 13
#*: They '''weep''' unto me, saying, Give us flesh, that we may eat.
# {{context|medicine|of a|[[wound]] or [[sore]]|lang=en}} To produce [[secretion]]s.
# To flow in drops; to run in drops.
#: ''a '''weeping''' spring, which discharges water slowly''
#* Shakespeare
#*: The blood '''weeps''' from my heart.
# To hang the branches, as if in sorrow; to be pendent; to droop; said of a plant or its branches.
# {{cx|obsolete|transitive|lang=en}} To weep over; to bewail.
#* Prior
#*: Fair Venus '''wept''' the sad disaster / Of having lost her favorite dove.

